# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emergency-department
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The explosions killed 193 people and injured around 2,500.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The bombings constituted the deadliest terrorist attack carried out in the history of Spain and the deadliest in Europe since the 1988 bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 in Scotland.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The attacks were carried out by radical Islamists who opposed Spanish indirect involvement in the 2003 US-led invasion of Iraq.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Controversy regarding the handling and representation of the bombings by the government arose, with Spain's two main political parties — the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party (PSOE) and the Partido Popular (PP) — accusing each other of concealing or distorting evidence for electoral reasons.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The bombings occurred three days before general elections in which incumbent Prime Minister José María Aznar's PP was defeated.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The scale and precise planning of the attacks reared memories of the September 11 attacks.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Results published in *The Review of Economics and Statistics* by economist José García Montalvo seem to suggest that indeed the bombings had important electoral impact (turning the electoral outcome against the incumbent People's Party and handing government over to the Socialist Party, PSOE).
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] After 21 months of investigation, judge Juan del Olmo tried Moroccan national Jamal Zougam, among several others, for his participation carrying out the attack.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Although claims were made that attacks were linked to al-Qaeda, investigations and probes conducted by Spanish officials did not find any links to al-Qaeda.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Findings issued by the Spanish judiciary in September 2007 found 21 individuals guilty of participating in the attacks, while rejecting the involvement of an external mastermind or direct al-Qaeda links.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] During the peak of Madrid rush hour on the morning of Thursday, 11 March 2004, ten explosions occurred aboard four commuter trains (*cercanías*).
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The date, 11 March, led to the abbreviation of the incident as "11-M".
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] All the affected trains were traveling on the same line and in the same direction between Alcalá de Henares and the Atocha station in Madrid.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] It was later reported that thirteen improvised explosive devices (IEDs) had been placed on the trains.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Bomb disposal teams (TEDAX) arriving at the scenes of the explosions detonated two of the remaining three IEDs in controlled explosions, but the third was not found until later in the evening, having been stored inadvertently with luggage taken from one of the trains.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The following timeline of events comes from the judicial investigation.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] All four trains had departed the Alcalá de Henares station between 07:01 and 07:14.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] At 08:00, emergency relief workers began arriving at the scenes of the bombings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The police reported numerous victims and mentioned 50 wounded and several dead.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] By 08:30 the emergency ambulance service, SAMUR (Servicio de Asistencia Municipal de Urgencia y Rescate), had set up a field hospital at the Daoiz y Velarde sports facility.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Bystanders and local residents helped relief workers, as hospitals were told to expect the arrival of many casualties.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] At 08:43, firefighters reported 15 dead at El Pozo.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] By 09:00, the police had confirmed the death of at least 30 people – 20 at El Pozo and about 10 in Santa Eugenia and Atocha.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] People combed the city's major hospitals in search of family members who they thought were aboard the trains.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] There were 193 confirmed dead victims, the last victim dying in 2014 after having been in a coma for 10 years due to one of the Atocha explosions and not having been able to recover from their injuries.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The total number of victims was higher than in any other terrorist attack in Spain, far surpassing the 21 killed and 40 wounded from a 1987 bombing at a Hipercor chain supermarket in Barcelona.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On that occasion, responsibility was claimed by ETA.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] It was Europe's worst terror attack since the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland on 21 December 1988.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] A device composed of 12 kilograms of Goma-2 ECO with a detonator and 136 meters of wire (connected to nothing) was found on the track of a high-speed railway line (AVE) on 2 April.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Spanish judiciary chose not to investigate that incident and the perpetrators remain unknown.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The device used in the AVE incident was unable to explode because it lacked an initiation system.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Shortly after the AVE incident, police identified an apartment in Leganés, south of Madrid, as the base of operations for the individuals suspected of being the perpetrators of the Madrid and AVE attacks.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The suspected militants, Sarhane Abdelmaji "the Tunisian" and Jamal Ahmidan "the Chinese", were trapped inside the apartment by a police raid on the evening of 3 April.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] At 9:03 pm, when the police attempted to breach the premises, the militants committed suicide by setting off explosives, killing themselves and one of the police officers.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Investigators subsequently found that the explosives used in the Leganés explosion were of the same type as those used in the 11 March attacks (though it had not been possible to identify a brand of dynamite from samples taken from the trains) and in the thwarted bombing of the AVE line.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Based on the assumption that the militants killed at Leganés were indeed the individuals responsible for the train bombings, the ensuing investigation focused on how they obtained their estimated 200 kg of explosives.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The investigation revealed that they had been bought from a retired miner who still had access to blasting equipment.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Five to eight suspects believed to be involved in the 11 March attacks managed to escape.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] In France, the Vigipirate plan was upgraded to orange level.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] In Italy, the government declared a state of high alert.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] In December 2004, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero claimed that the PP government erased all of the computer files related to the Madrid bombings, leaving only the documents on paper.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 25 March 2005, prosecutor Olga Sánchez asserted that the bombings happened 911 days (exactly 2 and a half years) after the 11 September attacks due to the "highly symbolic and qabbalistic charge for local Al-Qaida groups" of choosing that day.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 27 May 2005, the Prüm Convention, implementing among other things the principle of availability which began to be discussed after the Madrid bombings, was signed by Germany, Spain, France, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Austria, and Belgium.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 4 January 2007, *El País* reported that Algerian Ouhnane Daoud, who is considered to be the mastermind of the 11-M bombings, has been searching for ways to return to Spain to prepare further attacks, though this has not been confirmed.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 17 March 2008, Basel Ghalyoun, Mohamed Almallah Dabas, Abdelillah El-Fadual El-Akil and Raúl González Peña, having been found guilty by the Audiencia Nacional, were released after a Higher Court ruling.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] This court also verified the release of the Egyptian Rabei Osman al-Sayed.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 14 March 2004, Abu Dujana al-Afghani, a purported spokesman for al-Qaeda in Europe, appeared in a videotape claiming responsibility for the attacks.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Spanish judiciary stated that a loose group of Moroccan, Syrian, and Algerian Muslims and two Guardia Civil and Spanish police informants were suspected of having carried out the attacks.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 11 April 2006, Judge Juan del Olmo charged 29 suspects for their involvement in the train bombings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] No evidence has been found of al-Qaeda involvement, although an al-Qaeda claim was made the day of the attacks by the Abu Hafs al-Masri Brigades.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] U.S. officials note that this group is "notoriously unreliable".
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] In August 2007, al-Qaeda claimed to be "proud" about the Madrid 2004 bombings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Mohamed Darif, a professor of political science at Hassan II University in Mohammedia, stated in 2004 that the history of the Moroccan Combat Group is directly tied to the rise of al-Qaeda in Afghanistan.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Scholar Rogelio Alonso said in 2007, "the investigation had uncovered a link between the Madrid suspects and the wider world of al-Qaida".
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Scott Atran said "There isn't the slightest bit of evidence of any relationship with al-Qaida.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] We've been looking at it closely for years and we've been briefed by everybody under the sun... and nothing connects them." He provides a detailed timeline that lends credence to this view.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to the European Strategic Intelligence and Security Center, the Islamic extremists' alliance with ETA is highly dubious and "there is not anyway any terror case whatsoever to this day in which islamist internationalists collaborated with non-muslims".
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Former Spanish Prime Minister José María Aznar said in 2011 that Abdelhakim Belhadj, leader of the Libyan Islamic Fighting Group and current head of the Tripoli Military Council, was suspected of complicity in the bombings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Immediate reactions to the attacks in Madrid were the several press conferences held by the Spanish prime minister José María Aznar involving ETA.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Spanish government maintained this theory for two days.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Because the bombs were detonated three days before the general elections in Spain, the situation had many political interpretations.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The United States also initially believed ETA was responsible, then questioning if Islamic extremists were responsible.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Due to the government theory, statements issued shortly after the Madrid attacks, including from lehendakari Juan José Ibarretxe identified ETA as the prime suspect, but the group, which usually claims responsibility for its actions, denied any involvement.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Later evidence strongly pointed to the involvement of extremist Islamist groups, with the Moroccan Islamic Combatant Group named as a focus of investigations.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Although ETA has a history of mounting bomb attacks in Madrid, the 11 March attacks exceeded any attack previously attempted by a European organisation.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] This led some experts to point out that the tactics used were more typical of militant Islamic extremist groups, perhaps with a certain link to al-Qaeda, or maybe to a new generation of ETA activists using al-Qaeda as a role model.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Observers also noted that ETA customarily, but not always, issues warnings before its mass bombings and that there had been no warning for this attack.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Europol director Jürgen Storbeck commented that the bombings "could have been ETA...
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] But we're dealing with an attack that doesn't correspond to the modus operandi they have adopted up to now".
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Political analysts believe ETA's guilt would have strengthened the PP's chances of being re-elected, as this would have been regarded as the death throes of a terrorist organisation reduced to desperate measures by the strong anti-terrorist policy of the Aznar government.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On the other hand, an Islamic extremist attack would have been perceived as the direct result of Spain's involvement in Iraq, an unpopular war that had not been approved by the Spanish Parliament.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] All of the devices are thought to have been hidden inside backpacks.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The police investigated reports of three people in ski masks getting on and off the trains several times at Alcalá de Henares between 7:00 and 7:10.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] A Renault Kangoo van was found parked outside the station at Alcalá de Henares containing detonators, audio tapes with Qur'anic verses, and cell phones.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The provincial chief of TEDAX (the bomb disposal experts of the Spanish police) declared on 12 July 2004 that damage in the trains could not be caused by dynamite, but by some type of military explosive, like C3 or C4.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] An unnamed source from the Aznar administration claimed that the explosive used in the attacks had been Titadine (used by ETA, and intercepted on its way to Madrid 11 days before).
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] In March 2007, the TEDAX chief claimed that they knew that the unexploded explosive found in the Kangoo van was Goma-2 ECO the very day of the bombings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] He also asserted that "it is impossible to know" the components of the explosives that went off in the trains – though he later asserted that it was dynamite.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Judge Javier Gómez Bermúdez replied "I cannot understand" to these assertions.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] A radio report mentioned a plastic explosive called "Special C".
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] However, the government said that the explosive found in an unexploded device, discovered among bags thought to be victims' lost luggage, was the Spanish made Goma-2 ECO.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The unexploded device contained 10 kg (22 lb) of explosive with 1 kg (2.2 lb) of nails and screws packed around it as shrapnel.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] In the aftermath of the attacks, however, the chief coroner alleged that no shrapnel was found in any of the victims.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Goma-2 ECO was never before used by al-Qaeda, but the explosive and the modus operandi were described by *The Independent* as ETA trademarks, although the *Daily Telegraph* came to the opposite conclusion.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Two bombs, one in Atocha and another in El Pozo station, numbers 11 and 12, were detonated accidentally by the TEDAX.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to the provincial chief of the TEDAX, deactivated rucksacks contained some other type of explosive.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The 13th bomb, which was transferred to a police station, contained dynamite, although it did not explode because it was missing two wires connecting the explosives to the detonator.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] That bomb used a mobile phone (Mitsubishi Trium) as a timer, requiring a SIM card to activate the alarm and thereby detonate.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The analysis of the SIM card allowed the police to arrest an alleged perpetrator.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 13 March, when three Moroccans and two Pakistani Muslims were arrested for the attacks, it was confirmed that the attacks came from an Islamist group.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Only one of the five persons (the Moroccan Jamal Zougam) detained that day was finally prosecuted.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Guardia Civil developed an extensive action plan to monitor records corresponding with the use of weapons and explosives.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] There were 166,000 inspections conducted throughout the country between March 2004 and November 2004.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] About 2,500 violations were discovered and over 3 tons of explosives, 11 kilometers of detonating cord, and over 15,000 detonators were seized.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 3 April 2004, in Leganés, south Madrid, four terrorists died in an apparent suicide explosion, killing one Grupo Especial de Operaciones (GEO) (Spanish special police assault unit) police officer and wounding eleven policemen.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to witnesses and media, between five and eight suspects escaped that day.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Security forces carried out a controlled explosion of a suspicious package found near the Atocha station and subsequently deactivated the two undetonated devices on the Téllez train.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] A third unexploded device was later brought from the station at El Pozo to a police station in Vallecas, and became a central piece of evidence for the investigation.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] It appears that the El Pozo bomb failed to detonate because a cell-phone alarm used to trigger the bomb was set 12 hours late.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Sectors of the People's Party (PP), and certain media, such as *El Mundo* newspaper and the COPE radio station, continue to support theories relating the attack to a vast conspiracy to remove the governing party from power.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Support for the conspiracy was also given by the Asociación de Víctimas del Terrorismo (AVT), Spain's largest association of victims of terrorism.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] These theories speculate that ETA and members of the security forces and national and foreign (Moroccan) secret services were involved in the bombings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Madrid judge Coro Cillán continued to hear conspiracy theory cases, including one accusing government officials of ordering the scrapping of the bombed train cars in order to destroy evidence.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The public seemed convinced that the Madrid Bombings were a result of the Aznar government's alignment with the U.S. and its invasion of Iraq.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Before the attack, the incumbent Popular Party led the polls by 5 percent.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] It is believed that the Popular Party would have won the election if it had not been for the terrorist attack.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Socialist Party, led by José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero, ended up winning the election by 5%.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Socialist Party had called for the removal of Spanish troops from Iraq during its campaigning.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Rodríguez Zapatero promised to remove Spanish troops by 30 June 2004, and the troops were withdrawn a month earlier than expected.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Twenty-eight percent of voters said that the bombings influenced their opinions and vote.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] An estimated 1 million voters switched their vote to the Socialist Party after the Madrid bombings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] These voters who switched their votes were no longer willing to support the Popular Party's stance on war policy.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The bombings also influenced 1,700,000 citizens to vote who did not plan on originally voting.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On the other hand, the terrorist attacks discouraged 300,000 people from voting.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Overall, there was a net 4 percent increase in voter turnout.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Judge Juan del Olmo found "local cells of Islamic extremists inspired through the Internet" guilty for the 11 March attacks, rather than the Armed Islamic Group or the Moroccan Islamic Combatant Group.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] These local cells consisted of hashish traffickers of Moroccan origin, remotely linked to an al-Qaeda cell that had been already captured.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] These groups bought the explosives (dynamite Goma-2 ECO) from low-level thieves, police and Guardia Civil informers in Asturias using money from the small-scale drug trafficking.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to *El Mundo*, "the notes found on the Moroccan informer 'Cartagena' prove that the Police had the leaders of the cell responsible for the 11 March attacks under surveillance." However, none of the notes refer to the preparation of any terrorist attack.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The trial of 29 defendants began on 15 February 2007.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to *El País*, "the Court dismantled one by one all conspiracy theories" and demonstrated that any link with or involvement in the bombings by ETA was either misleading or groundless.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] During the trial the defendants retracted their previous statements and denied any involvement.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to *El Mundo* the questions of "by whom, why, when and where the Madrid train attacks were planned" are still "unanswered", because the alleged masterminds of the attacks were acquitted.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] *El Mundo* also claimed — among other misgivings — that the Spanish judiciary reached "scientifically unsound" conclusions about the kind of explosives used in the trains, and that no direct al-Qaeda link was found, thus "debunking the key argument of the official version".
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Anthropologist Scott Atran described the Madrid trial as "a complete farce" stating that "There isn't the slightest bit of evidence of any operational relationship with al-Qaida".
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Though the trial proceeded smoothly in its opening months, 14 of the 29 defendants began a hunger strike in May, protesting against the allegedly "unfair" role of political parties and media in the legal proceedings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Judge Javier Gómez Bermúdez refused to suspend the trial despite the strike, and the hunger strikers ended their fast on 21 May.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The last hearing of the trial was held on 2 July 2007.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 31 October 2007, the Audiencia Nacional of Spain handed down its judgements.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Of the 28 defendants in the trial, 21 were found guilty on a range of charges from forgery to murder.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Two of the defendants were each sentenced to more than 40,000 years in prison.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 31 October 2007, he was convicted of 191 charges of murder and 1,856 charges of attempted murder, and received a sentence of 42,922 years in confinement.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] A Spaniard, Emilio Suárez Trashorras, who supplied dynamite, stolen from a mine in Asturias in return for drugs – was sentenced to 34,715 years.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Neither is expected to serve more than 40 years, which in 2007 was the maximum prison term under by Spanish law.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] In the investigations carried out to find out what went wrong in the security services, many individual instances of negligence and miscoordination between different branches of the police were found.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The group dealing with Islamist extremists was very small and in spite of having carried out some surveillances, they were unable to stop the bombings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Also, some of the criminals involved in the "Little Mafia" who provided the explosives were police informants and had leaked to their case officers some tips that were not followed up on.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Some of the alleged perpetrators of the bombing were reportedly under surveillance by the Spanish police since 2001.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] At the time of the Madrid bombings, Spain was well equipped with internal security structures that were, for the most part, effective in the fight against terrorism.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] It became evident that there were coordination issues between police forces as well as within each of them.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Interior Ministry focused on correcting these weaknesses.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] It was Spain's goal to strengthen its police intelligence in order to deal with the risks and threats of international terrorism.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] This decision for the National Police and the Guardia Civil to strengthen their counter-terrorism services, led to an increase in jobs aimed at preventing and fighting global terrorism.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Counter-terrorism services increased its employment by nearly 35% during the legislature.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Human resources in external information services, dealing with international terrorism, grew by 72% in the National Police force and 22% in the Guardia Civil.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] This is a list of suspects and convictions related to the bombings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The authorship of the bombings remains a controversial issue in Spain.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Sectors of the Partido Popular (PP) and some of the PP-friendly media outlets (primarily *El Mundo* and the Libertad Digital radio station) claim that there are inconsistencies and contradictions in the Spanish judicial investigation.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] As Spanish and international investigations continue to claim the unlikeliness of ETA's active implication, these claims have shifted from direct accusations involving the Basque separatist organisation to less specific insinuations and general scepticism.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Additionally, there is controversy over the events that took place between the bombings and the general elections held three days later.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] In the aftermath of the bombings, there were massive street demonstrations across Spain to protest against the train bombings.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] Two people died in political violence about the ETA controversy.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] The international reaction was also notable, as the scale of the attack became clearer.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] A memorial service for the victims of this incident was held on 25 March 2004 at the Almudena Cathedral.
[src:emergency-department/2004-madrid-train-bombings] It was attended by King Juan Carlos I, Queen Sofía, the victims' families, and representatives from numerous other countries, including British prime minister Tony Blair, French president Jacques Chirac, German chancellor Gerhard Schröder, and U.S.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] An **acute medical unit** (**AMU**) is a short-stay department in some British, Irish, Australian and New Zealand hospitals that may be linked to the emergency department, but functions as a separate department.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] The AMU acts as a gateway between a patient's general practitioner, the emergency department, and the wards of the hospital.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] The AMU helps the emergency department produce a healthy turnaround for patients, helping with the four-hour waiting rule in the United Kingdom.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] An AMU is usually made up of several bays and has a small number of side-rooms and treatment rooms.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] They are fully equipped with emergency medical treatment facilities including defibrillators and resuscitation equipment.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] From the emergency department, patients can be moved to AMU where they will undergo further tests and stabilisation before they are transferred to the relevant ward or sent home.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] Also, patients can be admitted straight to AMU from their general practitioner if he or she believes the patient needs hospital treatment.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] A patient's stay in the unit is limited, usually no more than 48 hours.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] The AMU deals with admissions only, patients will never be transferred from a ward to the AMU.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] Surgical procedures are not carried out in the unit either; these are referred on to the relevant theatre such as cardiothoracics and general surgery.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] Senior staff in an AMU typically include a consultant in acute medicine, general medicine, emergency medicine, or critical care.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] Often a registrar in general medicine, and a ward sister or a charge nurse have roles in the unit.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] A number of staff nurses work alongside the senior staff to provide care to patients in the unit.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] Although AMU has its own staff trained to deal with patients and provide care, members of staff from other departments in the hospital are needed in AMU to assess patients and provide further diagnosis.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] Typical examples of staff who may be needed in AMU are general surgeons, cardiothoracic surgeons, cardiologists, and a psychiatric liaison nurse.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] The name "acute medical unit" is recommended by the Royal College of Physicians in its 2007 acute medicine report.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medical-unit] Despite this, many hospitals use different names for the department.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medicine] In medicine, describing a disease as **acute** denotes that it is of recent onset; it occasionally denotes a short duration.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medicine] The quantification of how much time constitutes "short" and "recent" varies by disease and by context, but the core denotation of "acute" is always qualitatively in contrast with "chronic", which denotes long-lasting disease (for example, in acute leukaemia and chronic leukaemia).
[src:emergency-department/acute-medicine] In the context of the mass noun "acute disease", it refers to the acute phase (that is, a short course) of any disease entity.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medicine] For example, in an article on ulcerative enteritis in poultry, the author says, "in acute disease there may be increased mortality without any obvious signs", referring to the acute form or phase of ulcerative enteritis.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medicine] Similarly, many acute upper respiratory infections and acute gastroenteritis cases in adults are mild and usually resolve within a few days or weeks.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medicine] The term "acute" is also included in the definition of several diseases, such as severe acute respiratory syndrome, acute leukaemia, acute myocardial infarction, and acute hepatitis.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medicine] This is often to distinguish diseases from their chronic forms, such as chronic leukaemia, or to highlight the sudden onset of the disease, such as acute myocardial infarct.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medicine] Acute care is the early and specialist management of adult patients who have a wide range of medical conditions requiring urgent or emergency care usually within 48 hours of admission or referral from other specialties.
[src:emergency-department/acute-medicine] Acute hospitals are those intended for short-term medical and/or surgical treatment and care which is a medical speciality of acute medicine, as often primary care is not positioned to assume this role.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] In individuals with supraventricular tachycardia (SVT), adenosine is a first line treatment used to help identify and convert the rhythm.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Certain SVTs can be successfully terminated with adenosine.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] This includes any re-entrant arrhythmias that require the AV node for the re-entry, e.g., AV reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) and AV nodal reentrant tachycardia (AVNRT).
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] In addition, atrial tachycardia can sometimes be terminated with adenosine.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Fast rhythms of the heart that are confined to the atria (e.g., atrial fibrillation and atrial flutter) or ventricles (e.g., monomorphic ventricular tachycardia), and do not involve the AV node as part of the re-entrant circuit, are not typically converted by adenosine.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] However, the ventricular response rate is temporarily slowed with adenosine in such cases.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Because of the effects of adenosine on AV node-dependent SVTs, adenosine is considered a class V antiarrhythmic agent.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] When adenosine is used to cardiovert an abnormal rhythm, it is normal for the heart to enter ventricular asystole for a few seconds.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] This can be disconcerting to a normally conscious patient, and is associated with angina-like sensations in the chest.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adenosine is used as an adjunct to thallium (Tl-201) or technetium (Tc-99m) myocardial perfusion scintigraphy (nuclear stress test) in patients unable to undergo adequate stress testing with exercise.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] When used to treat SVT, adenosine is administered intravenously as a rapid bolus (typically 0.10–0.15 mg/kg initially) over 1-2 seconds, followed by a rapid saline flush (often using a 2-way or 3-way stopcock).
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] If the initial dose is ineffective, it may be repeated every 2 minutes with a slightly increased dose (0.05–0.1 mg/kg increments) every 2 minutes up to a maximum total dose of 0.3 mg/kg (not exceeding 12 mg).
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] When given to dilate the arteries, such as in a "stress test", the dosage is typically 0.14 mg/kg/min, administered for 4 or 6 minutes, depending on the protocol.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] The recommended dose may be increased in patients on theophylline since methylxanthines prevent binding of adenosine at receptor sites.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] The dose is often decreased in patients on dipyridamole (Persantine) and diazepam (Valium) because adenosine potentiates the effects of these drugs.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] The recommended dose is also reduced by half in patients presenting congestive heart failure, myocardial infarction, shock, hypoxia, and/or chronic liver disease or chronic kidney disease, and in elderly patients.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adverse effects associated with adenosine administration are primarily due to its activation of adenosine receptors on vascular tissue, resulting in vasodilation.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Side effects of adenosine include skin flushing, lightheadedness, nausea, sweating, nervousness, numbness, and a sense of impending doom.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] These effects are typically very short-lived due to adenosine's rapid metabolism and short half-life.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Less common, but more serious, cardiovascular effects can occur, such as cardiac arrhythmias (including premature atrial and ventricular contractions and atrioventricular (AV) block), hypotension, cardiac ischemia, and prolonged asystole.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Dipyridamole potentiates the action of adenosine, requiring the use of lower doses.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Methylxanthines (e.g. caffeine found in coffee, theophylline found in tea, or theobromine found in chocolate) have a purine structure and bind to some of the same receptors as adenosine.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Methylxanthines act as competitive antagonists of adenosine and can blunt its pharmacological effects.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Individuals taking large quantities of methylxanthines may require increased doses of adenosine.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Caffeine acts by blocking binding of adenosine to the adenosine A1 receptor, which enhances release of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Caffeine also increases cyclic AMP levels through nonselective inhibition of phosphodiesterase.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] "Caffeine has a three-dimensional structure similar to that of adenosine," which allows it to bind and block its receptors.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Alcohol can increase extracellular adenosine levels.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adenosine is an endogenous purine nucleoside that modulates many physiological processes.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Cellular signaling by adenosine occurs through four known adenosine receptor subtypes (A1, A2A, A2B, and A3).
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Extracellular adenosine concentrations from normal cells are approximately 300 nM; however, in response to cellular damage (e.g., in inflammatory or ischemic tissue), these concentrations are quickly elevated (600–1,200 nM).
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Thus, in regard to stress or injury, the function of adenosine is primarily that of cytoprotection preventing tissue damage during instances of hypoxia, ischemia, and seizure activity.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Activation of A2A receptors produces a constellation of responses that in general can be classified as anti-inflammatory.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Enzymatic production of adenosine can be anti-inflammatory or immunosuppressive.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] All adenosine receptor subtypes (A1, A2A, A2B, and A3) are G-protein-coupled receptors.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] The four receptor subtypes are further classified based on their ability to either stimulate or inhibit adenylate cyclase activity.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] The A1 receptors couple to Gi/o and decrease cAMP levels, while the A2 adenosine receptors couple to Gs, which stimulates adenylate cyclase activity.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] In addition, A1 receptors couple to Go, which has been reported to mediate adenosine inhibition of Ca2+ conductance, whereas A2B and A3 receptors also couple to Gq and stimulate phospholipase activity.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Researchers at Cornell University have recently shown adenosine receptors to be key in opening the blood-brain barrier (BBB).
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Mice dosed with adenosine have shown increased transport across the BBB of amyloid plaque antibodies and prodrugs associated with Parkinson's disease, Alzheimer's, multiple sclerosis, and cancers of the central nervous system.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adenosine is an endogenous agonist of the ghrelin/growth hormone secretagogue receptor.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] However, while it is able to increase appetite, unlike other agonists of this receptor, adenosine is unable to induce the secretion of growth hormone and increase its plasma levels.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] When it is administered intravenously, adenosine causes transient heart block in the atrioventricular (AV) node.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] This is mediated via the A1 receptor, inhibiting adenylyl cyclase, reducing cAMP and so causing cell hyperpolarization by increasing K+ efflux via inward rectifier K+ channels, subsequently inhibiting Ca2+ current.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] It also causes endothelial-dependent relaxation of smooth muscle as is found inside the artery walls.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] This causes dilation of the "normal" segments of arteries, i.e. where the endothelium is not separated from the tunica media by atherosclerotic plaque.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] This feature allows physicians to use adenosine to test for blockages in the coronary arteries, by exaggerating the difference between the normal and abnormal segments.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] The administration of adenosine also reduces blood flow to coronary arteries past the occlusion.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Other coronary arteries dilate when adenosine is administered while the segment past the occlusion is already maximally dilated, which is a process called coronary steal.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] This leads to less blood reaching the ischemic tissue, which in turn produces the characteristic chest pain.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adenosine used as a second messenger can be the result of *de novo* purine biosynthesis via adenosine monophosphate (AMP), though it is possible other pathways exist.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] When adenosine enters the circulation, it is broken down by adenosine deaminase, which is present in red blood cells and the vessel wall.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Dipyridamole, an inhibitor of adenosine nucleoside transporter, allows adenosine to accumulate in the blood stream.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] This causes an increase in coronary vasodilatation.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adenosine deaminase deficiency is a known cause of immunodeficiency.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] The adenosine analog NITD008 has been reported to directly inhibit the recombinant RNA-dependent RNA polymerase of the dengue virus by terminating its RNA chain synthesis.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] This interaction suppresses peak viremia and rise in cytokines and prevents lethality in infected animals, raising the possibility of a new treatment for this flavivirus.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] The 7-deaza-adenosine analog has been shown to inhibit the replication of the hepatitis C virus.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] BCX4430 is protective against Ebola and Marburg viruses.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Such adenosine analogs are potentially clinically useful since they can be taken orally.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adenosine is believed to be an anti-inflammatory agent at the A2A receptor.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Topical treatment of adenosine to foot wounds in diabetes mellitus has been shown in lab animals to drastically increase tissue repair and reconstruction.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Topical administration of adenosine for use in wound-healing deficiencies and diabetes mellitus in humans is currently under clinical investigation.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Methotrexate's anti-inflammatory effect may be due to its stimulation of adenosine release.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] In general, adenosine has an inhibitory effect in the central nervous system (CNS).
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Caffeine's stimulatory effects are credited primarily (although not entirely) to its capacity to block adenosine receptors, thereby reducing the inhibitory tonus of adenosine in the CNS.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] This reduction in adenosine activity leads to increased activity of the neurotransmitters dopamine and glutamate.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Experimental evidence suggests that adenosine and adenosine agonists can activate Trk receptor phosphorylation through a mechanism that requires the adenosine A2A receptor.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adenosine in the brain acts through three major receptor subtypes—A1, A2A, and A3—distributed across various neuronal and glial populations.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Activation of neuronal A1 receptors generally exerts inhibitory effects, contributing to synaptic regulation.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adenosine has been shown to promote thickening of hair on people with thinning hair.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adenosine is a key factor in regulating the body's sleep-wake cycle.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Adenosine levels build up in the brain during periods of wakefulness, causing a need to sleep when levels become too high, and lowers during periods of sleep, giving a sensation of restedness when waking.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Higher adenosine levels correlate with a stronger feeling of sleepiness, also known as sleep drive or sleep pressure.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] Cognitive behavioral therapy for insomnia (CBT-I), which is considered one of the most effective treatments for insomnia, utilizes short-term sleep deprivation to raise and regulate adenosine levels in the body, for the intended promotion of consistent and sustained sleep in the long term.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] A principal component of cannabis delta-9-tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) and the endocannabinoid anandamide (AEA) induces sleep in rats by increasing adenosine levels in the basal forebrain.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] These components also significantly increase slow-wave sleep during the sleep cycle, mediated by CB1 receptor activation.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] These findings identify a potential therapeutic use of cannabinoids to induce sleep in conditions where sleep may be severely attenuated.
[src:emergency-department/adenosine] It also plays a role in regulation of blood flow to various organs through vasodilation.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In 2016, Adeptus Health was included on *Fortune's* list of the "20 Best Workplaces in Health Care".
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Adeptus Health was founded in 2002 with its first emergency room located in a Dallas suburb, Flower Mound, Texas.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Thomas Hall is the president and chief executive officer (CEO) of Adeptus Health.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Previously, Hall was the president and CEO of NovaMed.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In June 2014, Adeptus Health launched its initial public offering on the New York Stock Exchange with 4.9 million shares at $22 per share under the ticker symbol NYSE:ADPT.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Also in 2014, Adeptus created a joint venture with Dignity Health to open a hospital in Arizona.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In 2015, the company announced a partnership with University of Colorado's UCHealth to develop emergency care facilities in Denver, Colorado Springs, and northern Colorado, including 12 existing First Choice emergency rooms along with two new ones.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Adeptus also partnered with San Francisco-based Dignity Health to establish the Dignity Health Arizona General Hospital in Laveen, Arizona.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In May 2016, Adeptus reached an agreement with Texas Health Resources in which it rebranded 27 First Choice Emergency Rooms, and all of the FCERs in Dallas–Fort Worth, under the Texas Health name.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In August 2016, the company reached an agreement with the Mount Carmel Health System to build and operate emergency rooms in Ohio under the Mount Carmel brand.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Adeptus reached an agreement with the Ochsner Health System to build and operate emergency rooms in Louisiana under the Ochsner name in September 2016.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In April 2017, Adeptus Health filed for bankruptcy.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In October 2017 it announced its financial restructuring, which included the delisting of its Class A shares.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] After bankruptcy in 2017, healthcare-focused hedge fund Deerfield Management acquired control.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In December 2020, Adeptus filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Adeptus Health operates for-profit hospitals and a network of freestanding emergency rooms.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] It is the parent company of First Choice Emergency Room.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Prior to reaching agreements with healthcare networks, the company owned and operated 52 First Choice Emergency Room facilities located in Houston, Austin, Dallas, Fort Worth, San Antonio, Denver, and Colorado Springs.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Within Arizona, as of March 2017, Adeptus operated 10 freestanding emergency rooms that were co-branded with Dignity Health's Arizona General Hospital.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In May 2016, Adeptus Health reached an agreement with Texas Health Resources to align its First Choice Emergency Room locations and rebrand most of its Texas locations as Texas Health Facilities.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In August 2016, Adeptus reached a similar agreement with Mount Carmel Health System in Ohio.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] The case is *Oklahoma Law Enforcement Retirement System v.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Adeptus Health Inc.*, before Judge Amos L.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] Mazzant III in the Eastern District of Texas, and is under Sections 11, 12(a)(2), and 15 of the Securities Act of 1933, as well as Section 10(b) and 20(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In 2020, the court approved the payment of $44 million securities settlement to conclude the class action lawsuit.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] The settlement included all entities and investors who purchased Adeptus Class A common stock from 2014 to 2017.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] In 2017, a man from Colorado sued Adeptus and sought class action status involving the facility fees it charged patients.
[src:emergency-department/adeptus-health] It was alleged that the company took advantage of marketplace confusion and defrauded consumers through its failure to disclose excessive costs.
[src:emergency-department/admission-discharge-and-transfer-system] An **admission, discharge, and transfer** (**ADT**) **system** is a backbone system for the structure of other types of business systems.
[src:emergency-department/admission-discharge-and-transfer-system] An ADT system is one of four types of core business systems: ADT, financial, scheduling, and acuity (McGonigle, D., & Mastrain, K., 2012).
[src:emergency-department/admission-discharge-and-transfer-system] Core business systems are systems used in a health care facility for financial payment, quality improvement, and encouraging best practices that research has proven beneficial.
[src:emergency-department/admission-discharge-and-transfer-system] Used in health care, an ADT system is usually the foundation for other types of health care information systems because it holds valuable patient information such as a medical record number, age, name, and contact information.
[src:emergency-department/admission-discharge-and-transfer-system] Using the ADT system, patient information can be shared, when appropriate, with other health care facilities and systems (McGonigle, D., & Mastrain, K., 2012).
[src:emergency-department/admission-discharge-and-transfer-system] ADT systems can also be used as an alert system upon a patient's admission (Pittet, D., Safran, E., et al., 1996).
[src:emergency-department/admission-discharge-and-transfer-system] This can be helpful if a patient has had a history of an infectious disease or heart ailments.
[src:emergency-department/admission-discharge-and-transfer-system] When admitted, the ADT system may alert the admitting staff that the patient needs to be in an isolation room or on a cardiac floor, for example.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The emergency department is usually found in a hospital or other primary care center.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Due to the unplanned nature of patient attendance, the department must provide initial treatment for a broad spectrum of illnesses and injuries, some of which may be life-threatening and require immediate attention.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In some countries, emergency departments have become important entry points for those without other means of access to medical care.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The emergency departments of most hospitals operate 24 hours a day, although staffing levels may be varied in an attempt to reflect patient volume.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] It was further developed in the 1930s by surgeon Arnold Griswold, who also equipped police and fire vehicles with medical supplies and trained officers to give emergency care while en route to the hospital.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Today, a typical hospital has its emergency department in its own section of the ground floor of the grounds, with its own dedicated entrance.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] As patients can arrive at any time and with any complaint, a key part of the operation of an emergency department is the prioritization of cases based on clinical need.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Triage is normally the first stage the patient passes through, and consists of a brief assessment, including a set of vital signs, and the assignment of a "chief complaint" (e.g. chest pain, abdominal pain, difficulty breathing, etc.).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Most emergency departments have a dedicated area for this process to take place and may have staff dedicated to performing nothing but a triage role.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In most departments, this role is fulfilled by a triage nurse, although dependent on training levels in the country and area, other health care professionals may perform the triage sorting, including paramedics and physicians.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Most patients will be initially assessed at triage and then passed to another area of the department, or another area of the hospital, with their waiting time determined by their clinical need.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] However, some patients may complete their treatment at the triage stage, for instance, if the condition is very minor and can be treated quickly, if only advice is required, or if the emergency department is not a suitable point of care for the patient.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Conversely, patients with evidently serious conditions, such as cardiac arrest, will bypass triage altogether and move straight to the appropriate part of the department.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The resuscitation area, commonly referred to as "Trauma" or "Resus", is a key area in most departments.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The most seriously ill or injured patients will be dealt with in this area, as it contains the equipment and staff required for dealing with immediately life-threatening illnesses and injuries.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In such situations, the time in which the patient is treated is crucial.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Typical resuscitation staffing involves at least one attending physician, and at least one and usually two nurses with trauma and Advanced Cardiac Life Support training.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] These personnel may be assigned to the resuscitation area for the entirety of the shift or may be "on call" for resuscitation coverage (i.e. if a critical case presents via walk-in triage or ambulance, the team will be paged to the resuscitation area to deal with the case immediately).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Resuscitation cases may also be attended by residents, radiographers, ambulance personnel, respiratory therapists, hospital pharmacists and students of any of these professions depending upon the skill mix needed for any given case and whether or not the hospital provides teaching services.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Patients who exhibit signs of being seriously ill but are not in immediate danger of life or limb will be triaged to "acute care" or "majors", where they will be seen by a physician and receive a more thorough assessment and treatment.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Examples of "majors" include chest pain, difficulty breathing, abdominal pain and neurological complaints.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Advanced diagnostic testing may be conducted at this stage, including laboratory testing of blood and/or urine, ultrasonography, CT or MRI scanning.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Medications appropriate to manage the patient's condition will also be given.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Patients may be discharged home from this area or admitted to the hospital for further treatment depending on underlying causes of the patient's chief complaint.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Patients whose condition is not immediately life-threatening will be sent to an area suitable to deal with them, and these areas might typically be termed a "prompt care" or "minors" area.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Such patients may still have been found to have significant problems, including fractures, dislocations, and lacerations requiring suturing.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Children can present particular challenges in treatment.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Some departments have dedicated pediatrics areas, and some departments employ a play therapist whose job is to put children at ease to reduce the anxiety caused by visiting the emergency department, as well as provide distraction therapy for simple procedures.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Many hospitals have a separate area for evaluation of psychiatric problems.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] These are often staffed by psychiatrists and mental health nurses and social workers.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] There is typically at least one room for people who are actively a risk to themselves or others (e.g. suicidal).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Fast decisions on life-and-death cases are critical in hospital emergency departments.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] As a result, doctors face great pressures to overtest and overtreat.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The fear of missing something often leads to extra blood tests and imaging scans for what may be harmless chest pains, run-of-the-mill head bumps, and non-threatening stomach aches, with a high cost on the health care system.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Regardless of naming convention, there is a widespread usage of directional signage in white text on a red background across the world, which indicates the location of the emergency department, or a hospital with such facilities.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Signs on emergency departments may contain additional information In some American states, there is close regulation of the design and content of such signs.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] For example, California requires wording such as "Comprehensive Emergency Medical Service" and "Physician On Duty", to prevent persons in need of critical care from presenting to facilities that are not fully equipped and staffed.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In some countries, including the United States and Canada, a smaller facility that may provide assistance in medical emergencies is known as a clinic.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Larger communities often have walk-in clinics where people with medical problems that would not be considered serious enough to warrant an emergency department visit can be seen.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] These clinics often do not operate on a 24-hour basis.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Very large clinics may operate as "free-standing emergency centres", which are open 24 hours and can manage a very large number of conditions.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] However, if a patient presents to a free-standing clinic with a condition requiring hospital admission, they must be transferred to an actual hospital, as these facilities do not have the capability to provide inpatient care.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) classified emergency departments into two types: Type A, the majority, which are open 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year; and Type B, the rest, which are not.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Many US emergency departments are exceedingly busy.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] A study found that in 2009, there were an estimated 128,885,040 ED encounters in US hospitals.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Approximately one-fifth of ED visits in 2010 were for patients under the age of 18 years.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In 2009–2010, a total of 19.6 million emergency department visits in the United States were made by persons aged 65 and over.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Most encounters (82.8 percent) resulted in treatment and release; 17.2 percent were admitted to inpatient care.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Like an unfunded mandate, there are no reimbursement provisions.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Rates of ED visits rose between 2006 and 2011 for almost every patient characteristic and location.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The total rate of ED visits increased 4.5% in that time.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] However, the rate of visits for patients under one year of age declined 8.3%.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] A survey of New York area doctors in February 2007 found that injuries and even deaths have been caused by excessive waits for hospital beds by ED patients.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] A 2005 patient survey found an average ED wait time from 2.3 hours in Iowa to 5.0 hours in Arizona.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Three of the five Level I trauma centres were on "diversion", meaning ambulances with all but the most severely injured patients were being directed elsewhere because the ED could not safely accommodate any more patients.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] This controversial practice was banned in Massachusetts (except for major incidents, such as a fire in the ED), effective 1 January 2009; in response, hospitals have devoted more staff to the ED at peak times and moved some elective procedures to non-peak times.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In 2009, there were 1,800 EDs in the country.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In 2011, about 421 out of every 1,000 people in the United States visited the emergency department; five times as many were discharged as were admitted.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Rural areas are the highest rate of ED visits (502 per 1,000 population) and large metro counties had the lowest (319 visits per 1,000 population).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] By region, the Midwest had the highest rate of ED visits (460 per 1,000 population) and Western States had the lowest (321 visits per 1,000 population).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In addition to the normal hospital based emergency departments a trend has developed in some states (including Texas and Colorado) of emergency departments not attached to hospitals.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] These new emergency departments are referred to as free standing emergency departments.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The rationale for these operations is the ability to operate outside of hospital policies that may lead to increased wait times and reduced patient satisfaction.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] These departments have attracted controversy due to consumer confusion around their prices and insurance coverage.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In 2017, the largest operator, Adeptus Health, declared bankruptcy.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Patients may visit the emergency room for non-emergencies, which typically costs the patient and the managed care insurance company more, and therefore the insurance company may apply utilization management to deny coverage.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In 2004, a study found that emergency room visits were the most common reason for appealing disputes over coverage after receiving service.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In 2017, Anthem expanded this denial coverage more broadly, provoking public policy reactions.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Emergency departments in the military benefit from the added support of enlisted personnel who are capable of performing a wide variety of tasks they have been trained for through specialized military schooling.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Often, some civilian education and/or certification will be required, such as an EMT certification, in case of the need to provide care outside the base where the member is stationed.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The presence of highly trained enlisted personnel in an emergency department drastically reduces the workload on nurses and doctors.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] All accident and emergency (A&E) departments throughout the United Kingdom are financed and managed publicly by the National Health Service (NHS of each constituent country: England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The term "A&E" is widely recognised and used rather than the full name; it is used on road signs, official documentation, etc.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In Wales the Welsh name for A&E is *Uned Achosion Brys* ('Emergency Unit'), while the Scottish Gaelic term is *aigreid agus èigean* ('accident and emergency') but is not used on official signage.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] A&E services are provided to all, without charge.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Other NHS medical care, including hospital treatment following an emergency, is free of charge only to all who are "ordinarily resident" in Britain; residency rather than citizenship is the criterion (details on charges vary from country to country).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Historically, waits for assessment in A&E were very long in some areas of the UK.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In October 2002, the Department of Health introduced a four-hour target in emergency departments that required departments in England to assess and treat patients within four hours of arrival, with referral and assessment by other departments if deemed necessary.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] It was expected that the patients would have physically left the department within the four hours.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Present policy is that 95% of all patient cases do not "breach" this four-hour wait.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The busiest departments in the UK outside London include University Hospital of Wales in Cardiff, The North Wales Regional Hospital in Wrexham, the Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh and Queen Alexandra Hospital in Portsmouth.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In July 2014, the QualityWatch research programme published in-depth analysis which tracked 41 million A&E attendances from 2010 to 2013.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] This showed that the number of patients in a department at any one time was closely linked to waiting times, and that crowding in A&E had increased as a result of a growing and ageing population, compounded by the freezing or reduction of A&E capacity.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Between 2010/11 and 2012/13 crowding increased by 8%, despite a rise of just 3% in A&E visits, and this trend looks set to continue.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Other influential factors identified by the report included temperature (with both hotter and colder weather pushing up A&E visits), staffing and inpatient bed numbers.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] A&E services in the UK are often the focus of a great deal of media and political interest, and data on A&E performance is published weekly.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] However, this is only one part of a complex urgent and emergency care system.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Reducing A&E waiting times therefore requires a comprehensive, coordinated strategy across a range of related services.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Many A&E departments are crowded and confusing.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Many of those attending are understandably anxious, and some are mentally ill, and especially at night are under the influence of alcohol or other substances.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Pearson Lloyd's redesign – 'A Better A&E' – is claimed to have reduced aggression against hospital staff in the departments by 50 per cent.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] A system of environmental signage provides location-specific information for patients.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Screens provide live information about how many cases are being handled and the current status of the A&E department.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Waiting times for patients to be seen at A&E were rising in the years leading up to 2020, and were hugely worsened during the COVID-19 pandemic that started in 2020.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In response to the year-on-year increasing pressure on A&E units, followed by the unprecedented effects of the COVID-19 pandemic, the NHS in late 2020 proposed a radical change to handling of urgent and emergency care, separating "emergency" and "urgent".
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Emergencies are *life-threatening illnesses or accidents which require immediate, intensive treatment.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Services that should be accessed in an emergency include ambulance (via 999) and emergency departments*.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Urgent requirements are for *an illness or injury that requires urgent attention but is not a life-threatening situation.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Urgent care services include a phone consultation through the NHS111 Clinical Assessment Service, pharmacy advice, out-of-hours GP appointments, and/or referral to an urgent treatment centre (UTC)*.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] As part of the response, walk-in Urgent Treatment Centres (UTC) were created.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] People potentially needing A&E treatment are recommended to phone the NHS111 line, which will either book an arrival time for A&E, or recommend a more appropriate procedure.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Cardiac arrest is a sudden (in most cases, unexpected) loss of heart function, breathing, and consciousness.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] This emergency usually results from an electrical disturbance in the heart that disrupts its pumping action, stopping blood flow to the rest of the body.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] It is different from a heart attack, where blood flow to a part of the heart is blocked.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Cardiac arrest may occur in the ED/A&E or a patient may be transported by ambulance to the emergency department already in this state.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Treatment is basic life support, Automated External Defibrillator (AED), and advanced life support as taught in advanced life support and advanced cardiac life support courses.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Cardiac arrest is not a condition that can be self-diagnosed.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] It requires immediate medical attention and diagnosis by a healthcare professional.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Patients arriving at the emergency department with a myocardial infarction (heart attack) are likely to be triaged to the resuscitation area.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] An ECG that reveals ST segment elevation suggests complete blockage of one of the main coronary arteries.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] These patients require immediate reperfusion (re-opening) of the occluded vessel.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] This can be achieved in two ways: thrombolysis (clot-busting medication) or percutaneous transluminal coronary angioplasty (PTCA).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Both of these are effective in reducing significantly the mortality of myocardial infarction.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Many centers are now moving to the use of PTCA as it is somewhat more effective than thrombolysis if it can be administered early.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] This may involve transfer to a nearby facility with facilities for angioplasty.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Major trauma, the term for patients with multiple injuries, often from a motor vehicle crash or a major fall, is initially handled in the Emergency Department.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] However, trauma is a separate (surgical) specialty from emergency medicine (which is itself a medical specialty, and has certifications in the United States from the American Board of Emergency Medicine).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Trauma is treated by a trauma team who have been trained using the principles taught in the internationally recognized Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) course of the American College of Surgeons.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Some other international training bodies have started to run similar courses based on the same principles.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The services that are provided in an emergency department can range from x-rays and the setting of broken bones to those of a full-scale trauma centre.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] A patient's chance of survival is greatly improved if the patient receives definitive treatment (i.e. surgery or reperfusion) within one hour of an accident (such as a car accident) or onset of acute illness (such as a heart attack).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] This critical time frame is commonly known as the "golden hour".
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Some emergency departments in smaller hospitals are located near a helipad which is used by helicopters to transport a patient to a trauma centre.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] This inter-hospital transfer is often done when a patient requires advanced medical care unavailable at the local facility.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In such cases the emergency department can only stabilize the patient for transport.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Some patients arrive at an emergency department for a complaint of mental illness.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In many jurisdictions (including many U.S. states), patients who appear to be mentally ill and to present a danger to themselves or others may be brought against their will to an emergency department by law enforcement officers for psychiatric examination.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The emergency department conducts medical clearance rather than treats acute behavioral disorders.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] From the emergency department, patients with significant mental illness will be transferred to a psychiatric unit (in many cases involuntarily).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In recent years, EmPATH units have been developed in the United States to relieve pressure on hospital emergency departments and improve the treatment of psychiatric emergencies.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Emergency departments are often the first point of contact with healthcare for people who self-harm.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] As such they are crucial in supporting them and can play a role in preventing suicide.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] At the same time, according to a study conducted in England, people who self-harm often experience that they do not receive meaningful care at the emergency department.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Higher ambient temperature may also increase mental illness related emergency department presentations, particularly in females.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Noninvasive ventilation in the ED has reduced the requirement for tracheal intubation in many cases of severe exacerbations of COPD.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] An ED requires different equipment and different approaches than most other hospital divisions.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Patients frequently arrive with unstable conditions, and so must be treated quickly.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] They may be unconscious, and information such as their medical history, allergies, and blood type may be unavailable.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] ED staff are trained to work quickly and effectively even with minimal information.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] ED staff must also interact efficiently with pre-hospital care providers such as EMTs, paramedics, and others who are occasionally based in an ED.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The pre-hospital providers may use equipment unfamiliar to the average physician, but ED physicians must be expert in using (and safely removing) specialized equipment, since devices such as military anti-shock trousers ("MAST") and traction splints require special procedures.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Among other reasons, given that they must be able to handle specialized equipment, physicians can now specialize in emergency medicine, and EDs employ many such specialists.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] ED staff have much in common with ambulance and fire crews, combat medics, search and rescue teams, and disaster response teams.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Often, joint training and practice drills are organized to improve the coordination of this complex response system.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Busy EDs exchange a great deal of equipment with ambulance crews, and both must provide for replacing, returning, or reimbursing for costly items.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Cardiac arrest and major trauma are relatively common in EDs, so defibrillators, automatic ventilation and CPR machines, and bleeding control dressings are used heavily.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Survival in such cases is greatly enhanced by shortening the wait for key interventions, and in recent years some of this specialized equipment has spread to pre-hospital settings.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The best-known example is defibrillators, which spread first to ambulances, then in an automatic version to police cars and fire apparatus, and most recently to public spaces such as airports, office buildings, hotels, and even shopping malls.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Because time is such an essential factor in emergency treatment, EDs typically have their own diagnostic equipment to avoid waiting for equipment installed elsewhere in the hospital.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Nearly all have radiographic examination rooms staffed by dedicated radiographers, and many now have full radiology facilities including CT scanners and ultrasonography equipment.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Laboratory services may be handled on a priority basis by the hospital lab, or the ED may have its own "STAT Lab" for basic labs (blood counts, blood typing, toxicology screens, etc.) that must be returned very rapidly.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Metrics applicable to the ED can be grouped into three main categories, volume, cycle time, and patient satisfaction.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Volume metrics including arrivals per hour, percentage of ED beds occupied, and age of patients are understood at a basic level at all hospitals as an indication for staffing requirements.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Cycle time metrics are the mainstays of the evaluation and tracking of process efficiency and are less widespread since an active effort is needed to collect and analyze this data.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Patient satisfaction metrics, already commonly collected by nursing groups, physician groups, and hospitals, are useful in demonstrating the impact of changes in patient perception of care over time.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Since patient satisfaction metrics are derivative and subjective, they are less useful in primary process improvement.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Health information exchanges can reduce nonurgent ED visits by supplying current data about admissions, discharges, and transfers to health plans and accountable care organizations, allowing them to shift ED use to primary care settings.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In all primary care trusts there are out of hours medical consultations provided by general practitioners or nurse practitioners.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In the United States, barriers to accessing care contribute to frequent emergency room use.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Notably, certain complaints may also be addressed by a telephone call to a person's primary care provider.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] However, subsequent studies have shown that identifying non-emergency visits based on discharge diagnoses is inaccurate because people commonly present for emergency care for other reasons and are assigned a diagnosis after testing and evaluation.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] In the United States, and many other countries, hospitals are beginning to create areas in their emergency rooms for people with minor injuries.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] These are commonly referred as *Fast Track* or *Minor Care* units.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] These units are for people with non-life-threatening injuries.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The use of these units within a department have been shown to significantly improve the flow of patients through a department and to reduce waiting times.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Urgent care clinics are another alternative, where patients can go to receive immediate care for non-life-threatening conditions.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] To reduce the strain on limited ED resources, American Medical Response created a checklist that allows EMTs to identify intoxicated individuals who can be safely sent to detoxification facilities instead.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Emergency department overcrowding is when function of a department is hindered by an inability to treat all patients in an adequate manner.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] This is a common occurrence in emergency departments worldwide.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Overcrowding causes inadequate patient care which leads to poorer patient outcomes.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] To address this problem, escalation policies are used by emergency departments when responding to an increase in demand (e.g., a sudden inflow of patients) or a reduction in capacity (e.g., a lack of beds to admit patients).
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The policies aim to maintain the ability to deliver patient care, without compromising safety, by modifying "normal" processes.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Emergency department (ED) waiting times have a serious impact on patient mortality, morbidity with readmission in less than 30 days, length of stay, and patient satisfaction.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The probability of death increases each 3 minutes for 1% in case of major injuries in the abdomen part.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] (Journal of Trauma and Acute Care Surgery) Equipment in emergency departments follows the prompt treatment principle with the least possible patient transfers from admittance to X-ray diagnostics.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] A review of the literature bears out the logical premise that since the outcome of treatment for all diseases and injuries is time-sensitive, the sooner treatment is rendered, the better the outcome.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Various studies reported significant associations between waiting times and higher mortality and morbidity among those who survived.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] It is clear from the literature that untimely hospital deaths and morbidity can be reduced by reductions in ED waiting times.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] A significant proportion of emergency patients are discharged after treatment, but many require admission for ongoing observation, treatment, or to ensure adequate social care before discharge.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] If patients requiring admission cannot be placed in inpatient beds swiftly, "exit block" or "access block" occurs.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] This often leads to crowding and can lead to delays in treatment for newly presenting cases ("arrival access block").
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] This is more common in densely populated areas and affects adult departments more than pediatric ones.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Exit block can lead to delays for the patients awaiting inpatient beds ("boarding") and also for new patients arriving at an exit-blocked department.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Proposed solutions include changes in staffing or increasing inpatient capacity.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Frequent emergency service users are individuals who present themselves at a hospital much more often than non-frequent presenters.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Many frequent users are homeless individuals seeking shelter and food at the hospital.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Federal laws and regulations in the United States, like EMTALA and HIPAA, limit the options of hospital personnel when an individual presents to the ED with a fabricated problem.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] These individuals do not account for a significant number of visits but typically require a disproportionate amount of hospital resources.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] To help prevent inappropriate emergency department use and return visits some hospitals offer care coordination and support services such as at-home and in-shelter transitional primary care for frequent users and short-term housing for homeless patients recovering after discharge.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] A study found that telemedicine services in Saudi Arabia were effective in reducing emergency department overload by providing medical advice to patients with less urgent medical issues.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] According to a survey at an urban inner-city tertiary care center in Vancouver, 57% of health care workers were physically assaulted in 1996.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] 73% were afraid of patients as a result of violence, 49% hid their identities from patients, and 74% had reduced job satisfaction.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Over one-quarter of the respondents took days off because of violence.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Of respondents no longer working in the emergency department, 67% reported that they had left the job at least partly owing to violence.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Twenty-four-hour security and a workshop on violence prevention strategies were felt to be the most useful potential interventions.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Physical exercise, sleep and the company of family and friends were the most frequent coping strategies cited by those surveyed.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] Medication errors are issues that lead to incorrect medication distribution or potential for patient harm.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] As of 2014, around 3% of all hospital-related adverse effects were due to medication errors in the emergency department (ED); between 4% and 14% of medications given to patients in the ED were incorrect and children were particularly at risk.
[src:emergency-department/emergency-department] The ED is a riskier environment than other areas of the hospital due to medical practitioners not knowing the patient as well as they know longer term hospital patients, due to time pressure caused by overcrowding, and due to the emergency-driven nature of the medicine that is practiced there.
